  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These laws and frameworks are designed to promote international cooperation and establish common standards to prevent and detect money laundering activities. Here are some key international efforts and agreements:\n\n### 1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - The FATF is a global watchdog for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) efforts. Established in 1989, it sets international standards through its **40 Recommendations**, which provide a comprehensive framework for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n   - Countries that are members of the FATF or follow its recommendations are expected to implement laws, regulations, and enforcement mechanisms to address money laundering.\n\n### 2. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: This was one of the first international agreements to address money laundering, particularly in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (Palermo Convention, 2000)**: This convention requires member states to criminalize money laundering and establish measures to combat it.\n   - **United Nations Convention Against Corruption (UNCAC, 2003)**: This convention includes provisions to prevent and combat money laundering linked to corruption.\n\n### 3. **European Union Directives**\n   - The EU has implemented several **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** to harmonize AML efforts across its member states. The latest is the **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD6)**, which strengthens penalties and expands the scope of predicate offenses.\n\n### 4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - The Basel Committee provides guidelines for banks to implement measures to prevent money laundering, such as \"know your customer\" (KYC) and \"customer due diligence\" (CDD) practices.\n\n### 5. **Other International Cooperation**\n   - **Egmont Group**: A global network of financial intelligence units (FIUs) that share information and collaborate on AML efforts.\n   - **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**: These organizations provide technical assistance and support to countries in implementing AML frameworks.\n\n### Key Principles in International AML Laws\n- Criminalization of money laundering.\n- Establishment of financial intelligence units (FIUs).\n- Implementation of KYC and CDD requirements.\n- Reporting of suspicious transactions.\n- International cooperation and information sharing.\n\nWhile these international frameworks provide guidelines, individual countries are responsible for enacting and enforcing their own AML laws domestically. Compliance with these international standards is often monitored by the FATF and other bodies.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
